===Etymology===
From {{der|en|enm|abatement}}, from {{der|en|xno|abatre||to abate}} (from {{der|en|fro|abatre}})<ref name=CH>{{R:CDOE|page=2}}</ref>, + {{m|fro|-ment}};<ref name = WI3>{{R:MW3 1976}}</ref> equivalent to {{suffix|en|abate|ment}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en|en-us-abatement.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{a|US|UK}} {{IPA|en|/əˈbeɪt.mənt/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# The act of [[abating]], or the state of being [[abate]]d; a [[lessening]], [[diminution]], or reduction; a [[moderation]]; removal or putting an end to; the suppression. {{defdate|First attested from 1340 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=2}}</ref><ref name=CH/>
#: {{ux|en|The '''abatement''' of a nuisance is the suppression thereof.}}
# {{lb|en|legal}} The action of a person that abates, or without proper authority enters a residence after the death of the owner and before the heir takes possession.<ref name=WI3/>
# {{lb|en|legal}} The reduction of the proceeds of a will, when the debts have not yet been satisfied; the reduction of taxes due.<ref>{{R:RHCD|page=1}}</ref>{{defdate|First attested around 1150 to 1350.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# An amount abated; that which is taken away by way of reduction; [[deduction]]; [[decrease]]; a [[rebate]] or [[discount]] allowed; in particular from a tax. {{defdate|Late 15<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{senseid|en|heraldry}} {{lb|en|heraldry}} A mark of [[dishonor]] on an [[escutcheon]]; any [[figure]] added to the [[coat of arms]] tending to lower the [[dignity]] or [[station]] of the [[bearer]].<ref name =WI3/>{{defdate|Early 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{lb|en|Scotland}} Waste of [[stuff]] in preparing to [[size]]. <ref name=DSL>{{R:DSL|pos=n}}</ref>

